                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113Airplanes/2: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-08-05T15:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 5, 1926—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>157. Your 162, April 3, 2 p.m., 309, July 30, 5 p.m. Department’s 80, April 13, 3
                    p.m.</p>
                <p>You are authorized in your discretion to discuss question of possible
                    cancellation China arms embargo with your colleagues as suggested in your 162,
                    reporting result of discussion to Department. If information contained in your
                    309 can be officially confirmed Department would be disposed in the meantime to
                    amend present regulations to permit sale to China of commercial airplanes.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
